Infrastructure description

This infrastructure is a secured and monitored distributed web system hosting www.foobar.com
.

A user accesses the website through HTTPS, which ensures encrypted communication using an SSL certificate installed at the load balancer level.

The system includes a load balancer (HAproxy) that distributes traffic across three servers.

Each server is protected by a firewall that controls incoming and outgoing network traffic to improve security.

Each server contains a web server (Nginx), an application server, application codebase, and database components.

The database is configured with one Primary node responsible for write operations and Replica nodes for read operations.

Monitoring clients are installed on each server to collect performance and system metrics. These metrics are sent to a centralized monitoring system such as Sumologic for analysis and alerting.

Firewalls

Firewalls are used to filter network traffic and protect servers from unauthorized access by controlling allowed ports and connections.

HTTPS / SSL

HTTPS is used to encrypt traffic between the user and the website using SSL/TLS, ensuring confidentiality and data integrity.

Monitoring

Monitoring is used to collect system metrics and logs such as CPU usage, memory usage, and request rates. It helps detect system failures and performance issues.

Monitoring agents collect data from each server and send it to a central monitoring platform.

Monitoring QPS

Queries Per Second (QPS) can be monitored by tracking HTTP request rates at the load balancer or web server level using monitoring tools.

Issues with this infrastructure
SSL termination at the load balancer exposes unencrypted traffic between internal components.
Having only one MySQL Primary node creates a single point of failure for write operations.
Running all components (web, app, database) on the same server makes scaling and maintenance difficult.
